Form + Feeling 
“What makes me human? The answer to that is the answer to dance.” 
✊🏽
In celebrating Black History Month we want to shoutout some of our favorite pioneers and there’s no better place to start than the great Ulysses Dove! He was one of the most innovative contemporary choreographers of the past half century and many of his ballets are STILL the best ballet that companies have in their repertory.
✊🏽
His pieces echo the dynamic drive of Pearl Lang, the emotional strength of Alvin Ailey, and the nonchalant cool of Merce Cunningham, all of whom Dove danced with. But his unique style, characterized by speed and attack, earned him his own place in dance history, making his work important to preserve.
✊🏽
He has choreographed dances for ALL of your favorite dance companies, and he was also the Assistant Director of the Choreographic Research Group of the Paris Opera.
✊🏽
TDA Prep is proud to honor the black dance trailblazers that came before us.
✊🏽

SOUL FOOD takes its origins mostly from a collection of states in the rural South. During the Transatlantic Slave Trade, enslaved African people were given meager food rations that were low in quality and nutritional value. 
✊🏾
With these rations, enslaved people preserved African food traditions and adapted traditional recipes with the resources available. It’s the epitome of making something out of nothing!
✊🏾
Over time, these recipes and techniques have become the soul food dishes we are familiar with today. This food genre, now associated with comfort and decadence, was born out of struggle and survival.
✊🏾
There is so much history that can come from just one bite. 
✊🏾
✊🏾
✊🏾

“I’m going to keep trying, no matter what. Keep trying, keep on.” - Raven Wilkinson
✊🏽
TDA Prep is back with another shoutout to one of our favorite dance pioneers for Black History Month - Raven Wilkinson. Ms. Wilkinson was the first black woman to receive a contract to dance full time with a major ballet company, providing the black community a new standard and forcing the institution of classical ballet into the modern era. 
✊🏽
Raven Wilkinson’s dreams for dance began after seeing Ballet Russe De Monte Carlo, which she later joined after auditioning three times. But once you get the job, now you have to DO THE JOB in a still very much racist America. Touring brought danger to herself and her peers, and when the southern states learned of her race she was forbidden from performing. This ultimately forced her to resign.
✊🏽
After experiencing rejection after rejection in America, she moved to Europe to dance with the Dutch National Ballet where she danced for seven years before returning home. 
✊🏽
Raven Wilkinson paved the way for black dancers AND paved the way for the entire ballet industry to be taken seriously in a post-slavery world. TDA Prep is proud to honor the black dance trailblazers that came before us.
✊🏽

African-American social dances started as a way for enslaved Africans to keep cultural traditions alive and retain a sense of inner freedom. Black social dancing has steps that everyone can agree on, but it is also about individuality and creativity. Because of this, it just keeps evolving through the generations. The present will always contain the past. 
✊🏾
Here’s a list of modern dances that are rooted in Black culture and that are acceptable at any family function:
• The Electric Slide (set to Cameo’s Candy)
• Cha Cha Slide
• Cupid Shuffle
• Wobble (my favorite)
• Perculator

“The techniques that I knew and saw and experienced were not saying the things that I wanted to say.” - Katherine Dunham
✊🏽
TDA Prep is honored to finish our celebration of black dance pioneers for Black History Month with the “Queen Mother of Black Dance” herself, Katherine Dunham. Dunham pioneered a dance pedagogy fusing classical ballet with African and Carribean rooted dance and rituals. She was a remarkable dancer, anthropologist, choreographer, and founder of the first self-supported African American dance company. 
✊🏽
Dunham’s journey with dance started at a young age. Years later, when she went to the University of Chicago to study anthropology, she continued studying classical ballet, and simultaneously started forming the first all-black dance group and dance school. As an anthropology student, she visited the Caribbean islands. Her travels, specifically in Haiti, inspired her to create a unique dance technique combining the Caribbean and African ritual rhythm and movement with European modern and ballet dancing. She returned to the states informed by new methods of movement and expression, and went on to create the Dunham Technique that transformed the world of dance. In 1940, she formed the Katherine Dunham Dance Company, and toured all over the US and the world.
✊🏽
At TDA Prep, we love to “nerd out” with other dance nerds who train with us. Katherine Dunham is a perfect example of a true dance nerd. Her years in the Caribbean were spent studying all aspects of dance and the motivations behind dance. We frequently challenge our dance artists to explore the “why” behind their dancing. As we can learn from pioneers like Dunham, beautiful art comes from being honest with your “why,” so never stop nerding out!
TDA Prep is proud to honor the black dance trailblazers that came before us.
✊🏽
 #KatherineDunham #TheDunhamTechnique #BlackHistory #Dance #BlackDance #BlackDanceHistory #BlackHistoryMonth

We are TRANSFORMING the dance industry and it starts with DANCE PARENTS!
the FREE Dance Parent Workshop is back!
👨‍👩‍👦‍👦🩰
The next generation of dancers are growing up in your households RIGHT NOW, but how can you make the best decisions for them when you’ve never been a dancer and honest information is HARD to come by! WE GOT YOU!
 
DPW is the 2-Day LIVE workshop that gives #danceparents the need-to-know information for navigating the dance world and preparing your dancer for a GREAT quality of life in a professional career. We’re experts in the dance industry, and unbiased to your situation. This is the information presented exactly like you’ve always wanted and needed it.

Our hosts have over 30 years of experience with coaching principal ballerinas, athletes, and artists and dancing as a Principal Dancer with @alvinailey, guest with @royaloperahouse, actor in @netflix & @disney movies, model for @dior & @ralphlauren and SO MUCH MORE. (I told you, WE GOT YOU!)
💯
On DAY ONE, we’ll cover the ins and outs of training, performing, and competing, and how different activities can lead to a successful career in dance. You’ll also get a straightforward glimpse into the life of a professional dancer and learn about the different types of careers and their earning potential.

In-Person Week 3 is in FULL EFFECT! 🔥 This is not a convention, it’s not an experience... it’s pure, hard, training. Come get some! 👇🏽👇🏽👇🏽
💯
Twice a month dancers from all over the country come to The Shed to work on their technique, athleticism, and artistry away from their normal distractions. Our focus is in three different areas:

✅ We use Ballet, Horton, Graham, Contemporary, and Jazz and teach how TECHNIQUE can help all of those STYLES become more controlled.

✅ The purpose for technique is so that you have the control to make ARTISTIC decisions. We play games to embrace the imagination and study how to take what’s in your head and put it on stage. Sometimes there’s nothing in your head, and we have to do something about that!

✅ We work HARD, so that we get tired. When the body is tired and you challenge your mind to make mature decisions, you get better A LOT faster. 

These training weekends are NOT for the dancers that are afraid of hard work. This is about taking the normal student dance experience, and exposing it to the reality of what it takes to be a professional. IN-PERSON WEEK 3 is in FULL EFFECT! 🔥
